    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Corbin Carroll** (72.32) anchoring the outfield, serving as our premier daily plays. **Mickey Moniak** benefits immensely from the high-upside matchup against Sasaki; his profile is bolstered by a significant 19% boost in SP skill favorability and a dynamic platoon advantage that elevates him into elite territory. Similarly, **Corbin Carroll** remains a must-start despite facing a tougher arm in Gausman, as his elite xwOBA metrics and the premium stolen base environment created by his speed profile ensure his floor remains high even when the matchup difficulty spikes. **James Wood** (68.56) is our final strong-start pillar, capitalizing on a lead-off spot against a middling starter in Ray, proving that our emphasis on top-of-the-order speed remains the engine of this offense.\n\nThe most challenging roster decision today involved the marginal middle infield, where **Trevor Story** (57.63) and **Brice Turang** (58.40) narrowly held off **Jose Caballero** (49.74). While **Jose Caballero** offered a strong 13% platoon edge against Ragans, the optimizer favored the efficiency of **Trevor Story** and **Brice Turang** due to their respective high-probability stolen base environments\u2014specifically the slow delivery of their opposing pitchers\u2014which provides more value than the raw projection of our bench depth. Meanwhile, **Kyle Karros** (59.58) makes the cut solely due to a massive 19% SP skill windfall against Sasaki; though his spot in the 8-hole drags him down, his park-adjusted power potential makes him a viable start compared to the alternatives.\n\nRisk management remains paramount today, particularly with **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.63), whose score is suppressed by a negative platoon differential against Weathers. While he occupies a middle-tier spot in our lineup, we are keeping a close watch on **Austin Riley** (56.88), who faces the sharp Painter; any dip in early-game plate discipline could see his efficiency drop below the marginal 40-point floor. We have successfully avoided the basement, with **Luis Campusano** (35.80) and others benched to preserve our game caps. Stay vigilant regarding wind shifts in the late games, as any cross-breeze could turn our mid-range plays like **Max Muncy** (59.17) into liabilities if the park-factor boost evaporates.",
